description.value: Comparatively small but complete seal-impression in a round shape, at the rear several impressions of a 0.37 cm thick string that consisted of turned fibres around a protruding central mud part. Therefore the sealing probably originates from closing a bag or similar item that was closed by a string. The fine brown Nile clay has inclusions of mica. The clay was hardened after excavation before it was cleaned properly.  The front shows many finger impressions which also distort the oval scarab-like seal impression, leaving only a small area that is still recognizable. This part contains a circumferential band and a couple of hieroglyphs: maybe a nfr or Hr in front of a bird (maybe gm), behind it above a nb-sign, the rest is illegible. It looks like there might have been an earlier impression which then was covered by finger impressions and the new seal impression.

description.value: Comparatively large seal-impression with two rows of basketry coil impression at the rear and at the side one further rows, showing that this piece was positioned most likely on the lid of a basket. There are some traces from a string as well.  The fine brown Nile clay shows small inclusions of mica and was hardened after excavation.  The front wears many finger impressions around the oval impressions of a scarab-like seal. The motif is very worn, there is a circumferential line, several unrecognizable signs at the left and a cartouche at the right. There might be a thicker framing line on the right.

description.value: Fragment of a larger seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The rear shows two rows of basketry coil on one side and another row at a second side, suggesting that the piece was attached between the wall and a lit of a basket. The section is triangular. The flat front shows an impression of a larger oval scarab-like seal. Visible is a nfr-sign at the left, further right a seated baboon with a moon crescent above his head, facing to the left. Further right a lying ram at the right side, facing to the left, wearing the atef crown with uraei. Three hieroglyphs above his rear, difficult to identify.

description.value: Complete seal-impression, the fine brown Nile clay has some mica inclusions and was hardened after excavation. The rear shows two sides with each two coils of basketry, differing slightly in style, suggesting that the piece was attached between the wall and the lid of a basket. The top shows finger impressions and an oval scarab-like seal-impression. Visible is a standing figure with head of bull on the right, facing to the left a cartouche, which is preserved only in fragments, it seems to have a head of captured enemy at the top. At the bottom two horizontal lines.

description.value: Fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and partly a glossy surface. The rear shows two coils of basketry on one side and one row on the other, suggesting that the piece was attached between the wall and the lid of a basket. At the flat upper side one almost complete preserved impression of an oval scarab-like seal are visible. It shows a circumferential line and two figures. The one on the left is only partly preserved but seems to be an upright uraeus with a double crown, facing towards the left. On the right a standing deity, facing to the left, holding a staff in front of the body, probably Sekhmet, with a sun disc above the head. Between the two figures a small vertical sign, similar to aA (Gardiner O29).

description.value: Complete small seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation. The rear shows three sides (trapezoidal in section) with impressions that are difficult to define. One side shows compartments that might originate from a basket-like object, a second side is shaped slightly convex and the third side shows an impression of a turned cord with a width of 0.25 cm. The front side is convex and is covered in finger impressions. It shows most parts of a scarab-like seal impression, showing a lying crocodile facing to the left, underneath a standing bull, facing to the left as well.

description.value: Fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The rear is convex with the impression of leather, probably from a leather bag. In the break the impression of a turned cord with a width of 0.3cm is visible. The upper side is flat with the lateral sides bending downwards on one side and upwards on another side, and showing several finger imprints. about half of the impression of an oval scarab-like seal is visible. Recognisable is a wAs-sceptre on the left, in the centre an oval ring with a spiral inside in the shape of a sideways lying S. Underneath a nwb-sign. Same motif as on EA86905.

description.value: Fragment of a clay seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The fragment is broken into three fragments, bearing one seal impression of an oval scarab-like seal. The back of the sealing shows two flat surfaces, perpendicular to each other, and an uneven part in between that is quite blurred but could show impressions of cord.  The seal itself is shallow and blurry itself, showing an uraeus facing to the left, followed by a falcon, followed by another uraeus followed by another falcon with a sun disc and a flagellum. Above the first falcon another unidentified sign, maybe a boat? The same impression can be seen on EA86893 and EA86962.

description.value: Almost complete fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and partly a glossy surface. It also shows a blackened area, probably from fire.  The rear shows a small area with wooden fibres, probably from a bolt or a box knob, roughly perpendicular to this two impressions of a turned cord with a width of approximately 0.25 cm. Another part of the rear is slightly concave in shape (from a knob?).  The front side is convex and is covered in finger impressions. It shows an impression of a seal that seems to have been in the shape of a square cross with rounded ends. The motif shows a spiral pattern filling the complete seal.

description.value: Fragment of a small seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration with a partly glossy surface. The rear shows two sides with two rows of basketry coil each, suggesting that the piece was attached between the wall and the lid of a basket. The front has a small flat area with slightly downwards bending sides. On the flat area parts of an oval scarab-like seal-impression. Visible is a thin circumferential line. In the lower middle part a stylised nbw sign (Gardiner S12), above it a horizontal oval field with a line, inside a spiral that continued further to the left. To the left of the nbw-sign there is an ankh. The same motif is found on EA86820 and EA86920 and the latter shows that a small nfr-sign was positioned at the right end of the seal.

description.value: Fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and a very glossy surface. It also shows blackened parts probably from fire.  The rear shows a slightly concave area with the impression of wood, probably from a bolt or a box knob, perpendicular to this an impression of a turned cord with a width of approximately 0.20 cm.  The front side is slightly convex with finger impressions and shows part of an oval seal. The motif shows a standing falcon-bird, facing to the left with a flagellum behind his body. In front of the falcon another sign, probably walking legs (D54).

description.value: Fragment of a seal-impression, the fine brown Nile clay has some mica inclusions and was hardened after excavation. The rear shows one side with three small coils of basketry and a second side with two further coils of basketry, suggesting that the piece was attached between the wall and a lid of a basket. The front shows a largely complete preserved oval scarab-like seal-impression, slightly distorted and destroyed. Visible is a circumferential line, inside a kneeling male figure on the left, facing to the right with a lion to the right of it, having its front paws at the shoulders of the figure (probably a defeated enemy). Underneath the figure and behind the lion further signs that are no longer recognisable. This seems to be the same motif as EA86761.

description.value: Complete preserved seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The rear shows one side with flat impressions of two rows of basketry coil and another side with a deeper impression of a somewhat larger coil of basketry, suggesting that the piece was attached between the wall and the lid of a basket. The upper side bears two oval scarab-like impressions from the same seal and a small area that shows traces of textile (?) impression.  The motif of the seal shows a lying ram, facing to the left, wearing the double crown and in front as well as behind him D.t-snakes or similar as decorative framing signs. Underneath a division line a winged scarab filling the lower part of the seal.

description.value: Fragment of a small seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration with a partly glossy surface. The rear shows two deeply impressed turned cords with a width of 0.2 cm perpendicular to the impression of some organic material like wood or basketry. The front has a small flat area with downwards bent sides. On the flat area parts of an oval scarab-like seal-impression. Visible is a thin circumferential line. In the centre a cartouche with Mn-kheper-R' and on each side of it a small winged scarab rotated with its heads towards the cartouche. Same seal on EA86819, EA86897 and EA86899.

description.value: Fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and partly a glossy surface. The rear shows one side with a larger row of basketry coil and a second side with two smaller rows of basketry coil suggesting that the piece was attached between the wall and the lid of a basket. Recognisable is a lying ram, facing towards the left, wearing a double feather crown with uraei. In front of the ram a seated figure, probably MAa.t, facing towards the left. Above the back of the ram an uraeus with wings in protection gesture, facing towards the left.

description.value: Small fragment of a seal-impression, the fine brown Nile clay has some mica inclusions and was hardened after excavation.  The rear shows a convex rounded area like from a bag or suchlike (similar to EA86742, EA86756, EA86759 and EA86762) with the impression of a string of 0.25 cm width, a second thinner string impression perpendicular to the first one. The front shows the larger part of an oval scarab-like seal impression with a circumferential line. The seal is divided into three parts by vertical lines, in the outer two fields each a red crown. In the middle a symmetrical ornament, three out of four parts preserved showing each a raised middle part in a drop-shape from which two antithetical curled lines run of (like in the red crown).

description.value: Fragment of a clay seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The fragment is showing two seal impression of an oval scarab-like seal. Only the part with the seal impression has survived. The back of the sealing shows a small part with an uneven surface that is quite blurred but could show impressions of a wall (?) The clay shows voids of organic impressions and mica. The two seal impressions are underneath each other, they are shallow and blurry, showing an uraeus facing to the left, followed by a falcon, followed by another uraeus followed by another falcon with a sun disc and a flagellum. Above the first falcon another unidentified sign, maybe a boat? The same impression can be seen on EA86960 and EA86893.

description.value: Fragment of a clay seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The fragment is showing two seal impression of an oval scarab-like seal. Only the part with the seal impression has survived. The back of the sealing shows a small part with an uneven surface that is quite blurred but could show impressions of a wall (?) The clay shows voids of organic impressions and mica. The two seal impressions are underneath each other, they are shallow and blurry, showing an uraeus facing to the left, followed by a falcon, followed by another uraeus followed by another falcon with a sun disc and a flagellum. Above the first falcon another unidentified sign, maybe a boat? The same impression can be seen on EA86960 and EA86893.

description.value: Fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and partly a glossy surface. The rear shows a convex side with impressions of a textile or leather object, probably a bag. Two thin impressions of a string with a width of 0.15 cm. are visible in the break. At the flat upper side the left half of an impression of an oval scarab-like seal is preserved, the sides are bending downwards and show many finger impressions. The seal shows a circumferential line, in the middle a cartouche can be found (MAa't-kA-Ra)| on top of a nbw sign. To the left of it nTr nfr nb tAwy in a column, the part to the right of the cartouche is broken off.

description.value: Fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The rear shows a convex impression like from a vessel or similar object, in the break two impressions of a turned cord with a width of 0.30 cm. The front side is slightly concave and covered by finger impressions. In the upper part a seal-impressions, only the upper half is preserved. At the left a figure is facing towards the right, seems to be a stylized falcon headed god with a sun-disc above the head, the figure on the right is Amun, wearing the double feather crown, facing to the left and holding a wAs-sceptre in front of him. The rest is broken off. Black accretions on the surface. Same motif as EA86806.

description.value: Smaller fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and a partly glossy surface. The rear shows a convex side with traces of an object like a leather bag or a vessel neck, in the break one deep and wide impressions of a turned cord with a width of about 0.4 cm. Only a small part of the original surface is preserved with an impression of an oval scarab-like seal.  The motif shows a squatting Seth-animal, facing towards the left, in front of it very small hieroglyphic signs, a nfr on top of what looks like nb n, behind the head were another signs that are not preserved here. Same motif as EA86791.

description.value: Small fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and a partly glossy surface. The rear shows a small area with the impression of wood, probably from a bolt or a box knob, perpendicular to this two impressions of a turned cord with a width of 0.2 cm. The front side is flat running down towards the edges, covered with finger impressions and shows part of an oval seal with a circumferential line. The motif shows hieroglyphs, originally arranged in three horizontal lines from which parts of the middle and lower line are preserved. Visible is a seated figure at the left, facing to the right, next to it a khpr, in the lowest row the signs are not recognisable anymore.

description.value: Comparatively small seal-impression with two coils of basketry on one side, and another coil at the second side, showing that this piece was positioned at the lid of a basket.  The fine dark brown Nile clay has inclusions of mica. The clay was hardened after excavation, there is a crack on the surface. The front shows finger impressions as well as the impression of a scarab-like seal that was partly covered by a second impression that then was squashed almost completely by finger impressions. The seal motif consists of a circumferential band, a seated deity figure on the left, facing to the left, behind it a lying sphinx wearing a double crown and an uraeus as well as a beard, facing to the left. Behind the sphinx a cobra facing to the left holding its wings in front of it, between them a sun disc. Above and underneath it possible further illegible signs. Same seal as used on EA86700.

description.value: Quite tall seal-impression of clay, showing two smaller rows of basketry coil impression at the rear and at the side one further but slightly larger coil, meaning that this piece was positioned most likely on the lid of a basket as EA86673 and EA86674.  In the second coil an impression of a small square in which the lines are perpendicular to the basketry fibres, maybe this is a repair at the basket. The same can be found at EA86692. The fine brown Nile clay has inclusions of mica particles. The top part shows two impressions of a scarab-like seal close to each other, many finger prints around the seal impressions. The seal impressions show the same motif as EA86674 with a bird in the middle, facing to the left, in front of it two hieroglyphs (maybe nfr or nTr) on top of two small and flat signs like Gardiner N19. Behind the bird probably an uraeus. EA86674 also has the same impressions of basketry on the rear. The clay was hardened after excavation.

description.value: Fragment of a clay seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The fragment is showing two rows of basketry coil impression at the rear and at the side one further row, meaning that this piece was positioned most likely on the lid of a basket. The fine brown Nile clay has inclusions of small mica particles. The top part shows two impressions of a scarab-like seal, partly overlapping each other at the edge, and few finger prints around the seal impressions.  The seal impression are quite shallow and depict probably a bird in the middle, facing to the left, in front of it two hieroglyphs (maybe nfr or nTr) on top of two small and flat signs like Gardiner N19. Behind the bird maybe an uraeus. Quite similar to EA86673 but the cutting of the seal seems much sharper and better defined. The clay was hardened after excavation. Exactly the same seal impressions can be seen on EA86675.

description.value: Very small fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The rear shows a slightly concave surface with impressions of organic material like wood, maybe from a wooden knob or bolt. In the break one impression of a turned cord with a width of 0.2cm. The upper side is flat with about half of an impression of an oval scarab-like seal visible. Recognisable are two of three lines in hieroglyphs, the first one is only preserved on EA86918 showing a very small cartouche with at least 4 signs, but a crack is running through it. The second line is written from the right to the left: 'Imn-[R'], nfr, underneath the third row is written from the left to the right: Hr (D2) wDA.t (D10). The same motif is found on EA86918 and EA86919.

Recognisable are two of three lines in hieroglyphs, the first one is only preserved on EA86918 showing a very small cartouche with at least 4 signs, but a crack is running through it. The second line is written from the right to the left: 'Imn-[R'], nfr, underneath the third row is written from the left to the right: Hr (D2) wDA.t (D10). The same motif is found on EA86918 and EA86919.

description.value: Fragment of a clay seal-impression made of fine Nile clay that was burnt and now is completely black in colour like EA86955. The object was hardened after excavation and shows a shiny surface. On the rear on one side two coils of basketry, on a second side again two coils of basketry, suggesting that the piece was attached between the lid and the wall of a basket. The front is flat and shows one complete impression of an oval scarab-like seal with few finger impressions around it. The seal itself is almost completely preserved and shows three nfr signs next to each other in the middle. On top and underneath each a nb-basket framing the nfrs with the convex side to the ends of the seal. A finger impression partly covers the seal impression and a white accretion can be found on the surface.

description.value: Fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and partly a glossy surface. The rear shows a convex surface, maybe from a leather bag. An impression of a turned cord with a width of 0.2 cm in the break. At the flat upper side about half of a seal-impression is preserved with few finger impressions around it. Visible is a fine circumferential line, the remains of a figure wearing an atef crown and two winged uraei in front and behind the figure in gesture of protection. Above them very small hieroglyphs. The rest is broken off. Same motif as EA86893, showing a king holding a flagellum and a HKA-sceptre, facing to the left, at the bottom before and behind him cartouches, the one behind him shows (Mn-[kheper]-R')|.

description.value: Small fragment of a seal-impression. The fine brown Nile clay with some mica inclusions was hardened after excavation. The rear shows a concave surface with plant fibres, probably wood impression like a bolt or the base of a knob with one or two string impressions running perpendicular to the wood. In the break the impression of a twisted string with a width of 0.25 cm. The front side is slightly convex and covered with finger-impressions. A small part of an oval scarab-like seal-impression with a circumferential line is preserved, inside two small upright cobras underneath each other running of a central circled line like a cartouche. Small traces of the last sign, but not identifiable anymore.

description.value: Fragment of a clay seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and a partly glossy surface. The fragment is concave at the rear showing wooden impression, probably from a peg, in the break impressions of a turned string with a width of 0.22 cm. The front is convex and shows one impression of an almost complete scarab-like seal, with many finger impressions around it. The seal bears a circumferential line and shows a standing figure on the right side, facing towards the left. The figure is wearing a blue crown, one arm hanging down behind the body, probably holding an ankh sign, the second arm is positioned in front of the body holding a HqA-sceptre. In front of the figure a small cartouche (Mn-kheper-R')|. The same motif can be found on EA86936, EA86939 and EA86940.

description.value: Very small fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The rear shows a small concave surface with organic impression (wood or leather?). In the break two impressions of a turned cord with a width of 0.2 cm. The upper side is slightly convex with some finger imprints next to the seal. The lower two thirds of an impression of an oval scarab-like seal is visible on the top. Recognisable are two stylized standing figures holding a staff between them. The figure on the left is probably Re-Harakhte and the one on the right Amun. Both are positioned on top of a standing line. The same motif can be found on EA86902 and EA86911. The style is very similar to the motif of EA86792, EA86793, EA86799, EA86800, EA86801, EA86802 and EA86812.

description.value: Complete seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and a partly glossy surface. The rear shows one side with very clear impressions of two smaller rows of basketry coil and another side with one larger row of basketry coil, suggesting that the piece was attached between the wall and the lid of a basket. The upper side bears an impression of a complete small oval scarab-like seal and some finger impressions above it. The motif shows a Hathor sistrum (Y8) with a standing part like a nb-basket. Left and right at the base each an upright uraeus facing to the outsides. Very finely carved, even the eyes of Hathor are partly visible.

description.value: Quite large part of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and a partly glossy surface. The rear shows one side with very clear impressions of two rows of basketry coil and another side with again two rows of basketry coil, suggesting that the piece was attached between the wall and the lid of a basket. The upper side bears a deep impressed oval scarab-like seal and finger impressions. The motif shows a squatting Seth-animal, facing towards the left, in front of it very small hieroglyphic signs, a nfr on top of what looks like nb n, behind the head another sign, maybe a Hr? The rest is not recognisable anymore but there seems to have been a smaller sign behind the animal as well. Same motif as EA86796.

description.value: Fragment of a small seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration with a partly glossy surface. The rear shows wooden impression like from a bolt, perpendicular to it the impression of a turned cord with a width of 0.18 cm. The front has a small flat area with downwards bent sides. On the flat area parts of an oval scarab-like seal-impression. Visible is a thin circumferential line. In the lower middle part a stylised nbw sign (Gardiner S12), above it a horizontal oval field with a line, inside a spiral that continued further to the left. A small nfr-sign at the right end of the seal. The same motif is found on EA86920 and EA86923 and the latter shows that to the left of the nbw-sign there is an ankh.

description.value: Fragment of a small seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and partly a glossy surface. The rear shows one side with two rows of basketry coil and one side with one row of basketry coil, suggesting that the piece was attached between a lid and a wall of a basket. At the flat upper side is an impression of a very small oval seal visible. It shows a circumferential line, at the bottom a nb-basket and above the head of a ram, facing towards the left, wearing a crown that is not very well visible but looks like a double feather crown. There are many finger impressions around the seal and some black surface colouration probably due to a fire.  Same motif can be found on EA86945 and EA86949.

description.value: Almost complete seal-impression with two rows of basketry coil impression at the rear and at the side string impressions that were not cleaned before the object was hardened, showing that this piece was probably positioned on the lid of a basket.  The extremely fine brown Nile clay has mica inclusions and shows blackening from fire on the back.  The top is finely smoothed and uneven from the sealed object. One oval scarab-like impression is visible, showing three standing figures. The one on the left could be falcon headed and shows remains of hieroglyphs above his head. The middle figure shows Amun wearing a double feather crown. The figure on the right is not well preserved and therefore could be a third deity or pharaoh. The same motif (but probably not the same seal) was used on EA86716.

Underneath a very thin n line on top of a straight line, then a very thin mr-sign and a nb-sign at the lower end.

description.value: Fragment of a seal-impression, the fine brown Nile clay has some mica inclusions and was hardened after excavation. The rear shows two flat areas joined by a convex rounded area like from a bag or suchlike (similar to EA86732, EA86742, EA86756 and EA86762). Two impressions of a turned string in the break with a width of 0.2 cm. The convex top shows finger impressions a a small complete but slightly squashed impression of an oval scarab-like seal. It is cut very sharply with very small signs. Visible are three rows of three signs each. The top row shows a seated figure of Amun in the middle, the second a seated baboon.

description.value: Comparatively small seal-impression with a partly flat, partly convex rear, showing traces of a surface, maybe a leather or textile bag or similar, perpendicular to this a deep impression of a turned cord, similar to EA86689 and EA86690. The dark brown Nile clay has inclusions of mica and small charcoal bits. The clay was hardened after excavation. The front shows finger impressions as well as the impression of a scarab-like seal that is partly broken off at the left. The seal motif consists of a circumferential band, a standing figure on the left, facing to the right, towards a lying sphinx wearing a double crown and an uraeus as well as a beard. Behind the sphinx a cobra facing to the left holding its wings in front of it, between them a sun disc. Above and underneath it possible further illegible signs. Same seal used on EA86707.

description.value: Small but complete seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The rear shows two coils of basketry on one side and one coil of basketry on a second side, suggesting that the piece was attached between the wall and the lid of a basket. The upper side is flat with the lateral sides bending downwards, showing many finger imprints. About the lower half of an impression of an oval scarab-like seal is visible. Recognisable are two of three lines in hieroglyphs, the missing lines are preserved on EA86907 and EA86918. On EA86918 the upper row is preserved showing a very small cartouche with at least 4 signs, but a crack is running through it. The second and third lines are preserved on EA86907 and on this seal-impression EA86919. The second line is written from the right to the left: 'Imn-[R'], nfr, underneath the third row is written from the left to the right: Hr (D2) wDA.t (D10).

description.value: Fragment of a clay seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. On the rear on two sides each two coils of basketry, suggesting that the piece was attached between the lid and the wall of a basket. The front is slightly convex and shows one impression of a complete scarab-like seal, with many finger impressions around it. The seal shows a seated falcon in the upper left part, facing towards the left. Behind it a small cartouche, difficult to read, probably (Mn-kheper-R')|. The cartouche is not in the axis of the seal but askew following the outline of the rear of the falcon. Further to the right a lizard (I1) with its head pointing downwards. Underneath these three signs a standing lion (E22), facing towards the left, standing on top of another object that is bend like the end of the seal, a boat? The same motif can be found on EA86937.

description.value: Fragment of a clay seal-impression showing a concave rear with wood impression, probably originating from a peg or knob. In the break two impressions of a turned string with a width of 0.30 cm. The front shows one impression of a scarab-like seal, with the sides of the sealing bending downwards, many finger impressions around it. The seal impression is cut very sharply and shows a circumferential line that thickens at the top. The upper part of the seal is preserved, visible is a bound captive on the left side, kneeling, facing towards the left, with his hands bound together at his back. Behind him on the right a seated lion with its front paws on the shoulder of the captive. Behind the back of the lion a small upright cobra, facing to the right. The remaining part is broken off but she same motif can be found on EA86927, EA86928, EA86930, EA86932, EA86933 and EA86934.

description.value: Small complete seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The rear shows a slightly concave surface, maybe from a leather bag. One deep impression of a turned cord with a width of 0.25cm is impressed in the rear. The upper side convex and bends downwards to the sides. Two impressions of the same oval scarab-like seal directly parallel and next to each other are preserved with finger impressions around it and partly covering the impression as well. Visible are three columnsof hieroglyphs with a cartouche in the middle, from left to right: 1) nTr nfr nb tAwi 2) (MAa.t-kA-R')| nbw (Gardiner S12) 3) jTj(?)-HD (T25). 1) the good god, the lord of the two Lands 2) Hatshepsut 3) who takes the white crown(?). The same motif can be found on EA86815 where it is even clearer.

description.value: Small complete seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The rear shows a slightly concave surface, maybe from a leather bag. One deep impression of a turned cord with a width of 0.25cm is impressed in the rear. The upper side convex and bends downwards to the sides. Two impressions of the same oval scarab-like seal directly parallel and next to each other are preserved with finger impressions around it and partly covering the impression as well. Visible are three columnsof hieroglyphs with a cartouche in the middle, from left to right: 1) nTr nfr nb tAwi 2) (MAa.t-kA-R')| nbw (Gardiner S12) 3) jTj(?)-HD (T25). 1) the good god, the lord of the two Lands 2) Hatshepsut 3) who takes the white crown(?). The same motif can be found on EA86815 where it is even clearer.

description.value: Fragment of a comparatively small clay seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. Visible are two small rows of basketry coil impression at the rear. In one of them an impression of a small square (1.0x0.8 cm) in which the lines are perpendicular to the basketry fibres, as EA86675. Maybe this is a repair at the basket.  At the side impressions of slightly bent curve of other plant fibres. The rear of the sealing was not cleaned before the object was hardened and still shows remains of ash and small charcoal bits. The fine red-brown Nile clay has inclusions of mica particles and was burnt. The top part shows one impression of a scarab-like seal, surrounded by many finger impressions that also cover the seal impression and partly squashed the motif.  There is still the figure of pharaoh in a striding pose, having one arm raised to smite an enemy. Pharaoh is facing to the left, behind him a wAs-sceptre. description.value: Fragment of a clay seal-impression showing one large rows of basketry coil impressions at the one side and one smaller coil at another side, suggesting that the piece was attached between the lid and the wall of a basket. At the side a complete impression of a thumb. The clay was hardened after excavation leading to a darker discolouration. The front shows one impression of a scarab-like seal, with finger impressions around it. The seal impression shows a circumferential band that thickens in one part into a plant-like decoration in the upper right corner. On the left a falcon facing to the left, with a flagellum, right of it a small hippopotamus and on top of it a lying antelope or ibex with its head bent towards its back to the right. Underneath the hippopotamus and the falcon a lying crocodile facing to the left. The same motif is found on S9.

description.value: Fragment of a clay seal-impression, with a convex rear, showing traces of a surface, maybe a leather bag or similar, with some finger prints at the edge of it, perpendicular to this another side with deep impressions of turned cord. The object was hardened after excavation, the substance was not dispensed very well and left stains on the surface.  The top shows the half of an impression of a sharp cut scarab-like seal, with many finger impressions around it. The seal itself is only preserved in its upper half, showing a circumferential line and originally three registers, of which two are preserved. Each shows a row of seated deities.  The upper one starts left with a sA-sign, then Seth facing left and behind him a deity with a sun discand the moon crescent (Khonsu?). The second register shows another seated deity with a beard, facing to the right, in front of it remains of a khpr in the middle. The same motif can be found on EA86951 and EA86952. Here the second row shows a seated deit… (See Merlin record for full description)

description.value: Small fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The rear shows a concave surface with wood impression, probably from a bolt. One impression of a turned cord with a width of 0.35cm is impressed perpendicular to the wood. The upper side is roughly flat with the lateral side bending downwards and showing many finger imprints. The upper two thirds of an impression of an oval scarab-like seal is visible on the top, 0.4 cm further to the right another impression of the same motif is visible. Recognisable are two stylized standing figures holding a staff between them. The figure on the left is probably Re-Harakhte and the one on the right Amun. Both are positioned on top of a standing line. The same motif can be found on EA86902 and EA86915. The style is very similar to the motif of EA86792, EA86793, EA86799, EA86800, EA86801, EA86802 and EA86812.

description.value: Fragment of a small seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration with a partly glossy surface. The rear shows a convex surface like from a leather bag and perpendicular to this the impression of a turned cord with a width of 0.4 cm in the break. The front has a small flat area on which part of an oval scarab-like seal-impression is preserved, next to it another impression of a turned cord with a width of 0.45 cm. the seal-impression shows a thin circumferential line. In the centre a cartouche with Mn-kheper-R' and on each side of a small winged scarab rotated with its heads towards the cartouche. Probably identical seal on EA86819, EA86894 and EA86899.

description.value: Fragment of a clay seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and a partly glossy surface. The fragment is shaped convex on the bag showing impressions of textile or leather, probably from a bag and an impression of a turned string with a width of 0.22 cm is visible. The front is convex and shows one impression of an almost complete scarab-like seal, with many finger impressions around it. The seal bears a circumferential line and shows a standing figure on the right side, facing towards the left. The figure is wearing a blue crown, one arm hanging down behind the body, probably holding an ankh sign, the second arm is positioned in front of the body holding a HqA-sceptre. In front of the figure a small cartouche (Mn-kheper-R')|. The same motif can be found on EA86935, EA86936 and EA86939.

description.value: Fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and a partly glossy surface. The rear shows a convex impression like from a vessel or similar object, in the break two impressions of a turned cord with a width of 0.35 cm. The front side is slightly concave and covered by finger impressions. In the upper part two impressions, from both only the upper half is preserved. They originate from the same seal and show two standing figures. The left figure is facing towards the right, seems to be a stylized falcon headed god with a sun-disc above the head, the figure on the right is Amun, wearing the double feather crown, facing to the left and holding a wAs-sceptre in front of him. The rest is broken off. Black accretions on the surface. Same motif as EA86808.

The front side is slightly concave and covered by finger impressions. In the upper part two impressions, from both only the upper half is preserved. They originate from the same seal and show two standing figures. The left figure is facing towards the right, seems to be a stylized falcon headed god with a sun-disc above the head, the figure on the right is Amun, wearing the double feather crown, facing to the left and holding a wAs-sceptre in front of him. The rest is broken off. Black accretions on the surface. Same motif as EA86808.

legal.credit_line: © The Trustees of the British Museum

description.value: Small fragment of a seal-impression, the fine brown Nile clay has some mica inclusions and was hardened after excavation. The rear shows a slightly convex rounded area like from a bag or suchlike (similar to EA86732, EA86756, EA86759 and EA86762) with textile impressions. In the break a turned string with a width of 0.3 cm. The top shows a clear and deep oval scarab-like seal-impression with a lot finger impressions next to it. The motif shows a circumferential line with two standing figures facing each other, on the right Ptah in mummy shape with beard and a wAs-sceptre in front of him. On the left another figure, wearing a long kilt, both arms in gesture of adoration, the head is broken off.

description.value: Fragment of a clay seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and a partly glossy surface. The fragment is blackened due to fire. On the rear on one side two coils of basketry, on the second side another coil of basketry suggesting that the piece was attached between the lid and the wall of a basket. The front is slightly convex and shows one impression of a complete scarab-like seal, with many finger impressions around it. The seal shows a seated falcon in the upper left part, facing towards the left. Behind it a small cartouche, difficult to read, probably (Mn-kheper-R')|. The cartouche is not in the axis of the seal but askew following the outline of the rear of the falcon. Further to the right a lizard (I1) with its head pointing downwards. Underneath these three signs a standing lion (E22), facing towards the left, standing on top of another object that is bend like the end of the seal, a boat? The same motif can… (See Merlin record for full description)

description.value: Fragment of a small seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration with a partly glossy surface. The rear shows a flat area with the impression of wood, probably from a box and perpendicular to it the impression of a turned cord with a width of 0.2 cm in the break. The front has a small flat area with one preserved downwards bent side. On the flat area parts of an oval scarab-like seal-impression with finger imprints around it. Visible is a standing animal like a horse (?) with bent head and underneath turned by 180 degrees a crocodile with long tail whose curve follows the outline of the seal. The same motif is found on EA86895, EA86942 and EA86948.

description.value: Seal-impression made of clay, the back side shows the impression of three rows of basketry coils, the third one shows more than half of the coil which was probably the rim of the basket over which the clay was pressed, the side shows two finger impressions here.  The diameter of the basketry rim can be estimated to roughly 10cm. The upper part is roughly flat with the impression of a scarab base, showing a circumferential line, at the right a man standing in a striding position, faced to the left, holding a wAs-sceptre in front of him, the upper part of the figure is not preserved, left of the sceptre a large Shw-feather. Underneath the seal impression an impression of a string is visible as well, 0.3cm in diameter.

description.value: Very small fragment of a seal-impression, the rear shows impressions of either wood or other plants with a possible part originating from textile. Above this the impression of a turned string is visible.  The dark brown Nile clay has inclusions of mica and was hardened after excavation.  The top part is rounded and shows an almost complete and very small impression of a scarab-like seal as well as the edge of another impression that probably originates from another seal. Between them many finger prints are visible. The almost complete seal shows a standing human figure with an apron on the right, facing to the left, both arms erected as if it was carrying or offering something. In front of it at the ground further signs that look like a very small seated deity. Underneath either two lines or a nb-basket with inner lines. The second impression shows a horizontal line and a bent line.

description.value: Fragment of a clay seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and a partly glossy surface. The fragment is shaped convex on the bag showing impressions of textile or leather, probably from a bag and an impression of a turned string with a width of 0.22 cm is visible. The front is convex and shows one impression of an almost complete scarab-like seal, with many finger impressions around it. The seal bears a circumferential line and shows a standing figure on the right side, facing towards the left. The figure is wearing a blue crown, one arm hanging down behind the body, probably holding an ankh sign, the second arm is positioned in front of the body holding a HqA-sceptre. In front of the figure a small cartouche (Mn-kheper-R')|. The same motif can be found on EA86935, EA86936 and EA86940.

description.value: Fragment of a small seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration with a partly glossy surface. The rear shows a concave surface with very clear impressions of a wooden object like from a bolt, perpendicular to it two impressions of a turned cord with a width of 0.2 cm in the break. The front has a small flat area with downwards bent sides. On the flat area parts of an oval scarab-like seal-impression. Visible is a thin circumferential line around two probably originally three standing gods. In the centre Amun with the double feather crown facing to the right, only head and shoulders are preserved. To the right another standing god, facing towards left, maybe Re-Harakhte with a sun-disc above his head and above the disc a horizontal line.

The rear shows a concave surface with very clear impressions of a wooden object like from a bolt, perpendicular to it two impressions of a turned cord with a width of 0.2 cm in the break. The front has a small flat area with downwards bent sides. On the flat area parts of an oval scarab-like seal-impression. Visible is a thin circumferential line around two probably originally three standing gods. In the centre Amun with the double feather crown facing to the right, only head and shoulders are preserved. To the right another standing god, facing towards left, maybe Re-Harakhte with a sun-disc above his head and above the disc a horizontal line.

legal.credit_line: © The Trustees of the British Museum

description.value: Fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and a partly glossy surface. The rear shows a convex impression like from a vessel or similar object, in the break two impressions of a turned cord with a width of 0.15 cm. The front side is flat and covered by finger impressions, it shows most parts of a larger oval scarab-like seal-impression with a circumferential line. The lower part is covered with finger impressions. The upper part shows a standing figure of Amun, facing towards the left, wearing the double feather crown and a beard, both arms at the side of the body. Around the figure very small signs, in front an unidentified sign (seated goddess?), underneath possibly a wsr, in the lower part an ureaus. Behind the figure another unidentifiable sign visible in the upper part. The same motif as EA86808.

description.value: Fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The rear shows one side with a smaller row of basketry coil and a second side with two larger rows of basketry coil suggesting that the piece was attached between the wall and the lid of a basket. The upper side is flat and there are two flat impressions of the same oval scarab-like seal visible. Recognisable is the cartouche of Me[n]-kheper-[Ra](?) in the centre and to the left of it a cobra with wings in protection gesture. There are other hieroglyphic(?) signs to the right of it but not legible, maybe a standard underneath. The same motif can be found on EA86913.

description.value: Fragment of a seal-impression, the fine brown Nile clay has some mica inclusions and was hardened after excavation. The rear shows two flat areas joined by a convex rounded area like from a bag or suchlike (similar to EA86732, EA86742, EA86756, and EA86759). Several impressions of a turned string in the break with a width of 0.2 and 0.3 cm. The top shows finger impressions and a part of an oval scarab-like seal-impression. Visible is a horizontal sign that might be a plant or curled line, underneath a sign that could be either a standing lion or a dog with an inwards curled tail. The rest is broken off.

description.value: Fragment of a clay seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The fragment is showing impressions of very slightly convcave wooden object on the rear. The front shows a complete impression of a scarab-like seal with disturbance in the middle part of the seal, some finger impressions around it. The seal impression shows a circumferential line that thickens at the top. Visible is a bound captive on the left side, kneeling, facing towards the left, with his hands bound together at his back. Behind him on the right a seated lion with its front paws on the shoulder of the captive. Behind the back of the lion a small upright cobra, facing to the right. Underneath a bound captive, lying on his belly, with his hands and feet bound backwards. The same motif can be found on EA86927, EA86928, EA86930, EA86931, EA86932 and EA86933.

description.value: Small fragment of a seal-impression with impressions of basketry coil at the rear and at the side, probably from the lid of a basket. The fine brown Nile clay has inclusions of mica. The top part is broken away except for the most part of the impression of a scarab-like seal. It shows three figures in striding position and arms parallel to the bodies. The figure at the left is a falcon headed deity, facing to the right, the figure in the middle is Amun with the double feather crown, facing to the left. The head of the third figure at the right side of Amun is not preserved but the figure was facing to the left and was either a third deity or pharaoh. The seal impression looks like it was distorted by some plant remains or the seal was not cut very well. The same motif (but probably not the same seal) was used on EA86712.

description.value: 'Fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The rear shows a slightly convex surface, maybe from a leather bag. An impression of a turned cord with a width of 0.3 cm is visible in the break. The upper side is flat at the top and bends down towards the sides. At the flat part about three quarters of a seal-impression is preserved with few finger impressions around it. Visible is a fine circumferential line, a standing king wearing the atef-crown, with hands crossed in front of the chest, holding a flagellum and a HKA-sceptre in each hand, facing to the left. At the bottom before and behind him cartouches, the one behind him shows (Mn-[kheper]-R')|. Two winged uraei in front and behind the figure in gesture of protection. Above them very small illegible hieroglyphs. Same motif as EA86813.

legal.credit_line: © The Trustees of the British Museum

description.value: Very small fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and partly a glossy surface. On the rear a small surface with organic impression (wood or leather?). The break is not cleaned and might have string impressions. The upper side is flat with the side bent downwards and shows a small part of an impression of an oval scarab-like seal with finger impressions visible around the seal impression. Recognisable is a very small cartouche in the lower left part, something like xaj mn(?) R'. Further signs outside of the cartouche but barely readable.

Recognisable is a very small cartouche in the lower left part, something like xaj mn(?) R'. Further signs outside of the cartouche but barely readable.

description.value: Fragment of a clay seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and a partly glossy surface. The fragment is shaped convex on the bag showing impressions of textile or leather, probably from a bag and an impression of a turned string with a width of 0.22 cm is visible. The front is concave and shows one impression of an almost complete scarab-like seal, with many finger impressions around it. The seal bears a circumferential line and shows a standing figure on the right side, facing towards the left. The figure is wearing a blue crown, one arm hanging down behind the body, probably holding an ankh sign, the second arm is positioned in front of the body holding a HqA-sceptre. In front of the figure a small cartouche (Mn-kheper-R')|. The same motif can be found on EA86935, EA86939 and EA86940.

description.value: Fragment of a clay seal-impression, with a convex rear, showing traces of a surface, maybe a leather bag or similar, with some finger prints on it, perpendicular to this another side with deep impressions of turned cord with a knot. The fine brown Nile clay seems to be a bit lighter in colour than the previous examples and contains small mica particles. The object was hardened after excavation. The top shows the half of a deep impression of a sharp cut scarab-like seal, with many finger impressions around it. The seal itself is only preserved in its upper half, showing a circumferential line and a standing deity (possibly Thoth) on the right facing to the left, wearing a sceptre in front of it. Left of the sceptre a very small nb-sign. Above the deity another hieroglyph, maybe an n without the zig-zag lines or a p.t?

description.value: Fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and partly a glossy surface. The rear shows a slightly convex impression of a textile or leather object, probably a bag. Two impressions of a turned string with a width of about 0.2 cm. At the flat upper side the lower third of an impression of an oval scarab-like seal is visible, the sides are bending downwards and show many finger impressions. The seal itself is only preserved in its lower half, showing a circumferential line and originally three registers, of which two are preserved. The same motif can be found on EA86690 and EA86952. Each shows a row of seated deities. The upper one starts left with a sA-sign, then Seth facing left and behind him a deity with a sun disc and the moon crescent (Khonsu?). The second register shows another seated deity with a beard, facing to the right, in front of it remains of a kheper in the middle. Then the second row shows … (See Merlin record for full description)

description.value: Small fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The rear shows a slightly convex surface, maybe from a leather bag. One impression of a turned cord with a width of 0.1cm is impressed in the break. The upper side is roughly flat and upwards to the preserved side. The half of a somewhat larger impression of an oval scarab-like seal is visible. A standing finger is preserved in the middle, wearing the double feather crown and a beard, one arm raised behind his head, the other hanging down in front of the body from where a bent sign like a uraeus(?) continues. The very small hieroglyphs left of his head are a wsr and above a seated mAa.t with a sun disc above the head, underneath the wsr a small t-sign. The rest of the seal is broken off. The same motif but less clear is visible on EA86817.

description.value: Fragment of a clay seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. At the rear two coils of basketry are visible on one side and another coil of basketry on the second side, suggesting that the piece was attached between the wall and the lid of a basket. The front shows an almost complete impression of a scarab-like seal, few finger impressions around it. The seal impression is cut very sharply and shows a circumferential line that thickens at the top. The upper part of the seal is better preserved, visible is a bound captive on the left side, kneeling, facing towards the left, with his hands bound together at his back. Behind him on the right a seated lion with its front paws on the shoulder of the captive. Behind the back of the lion a small upright cobra, facing to the right. Underneath a bound captive, lying on his belly, with his hands and feet bound backwards, not completely preserved. The same motif can be found on… (See Merlin record for full description)

description.value: Part of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and a partly glossy surface. The rear shows a convex side with traces of an object like a leather bag or a vessel neck, in the break three deep impressions of a turned cord with a width of about 0.3 cm. EA86792, EA86793, EA86799, EA86800, EA86801, EA86802 and EA86812 all show the same motif and seem to have sealed the same object, the rear should allow a reconstruction of the sealed object.  Only a small part of the original surface is preserved with a small oval scarab-like impression and lots of finger impressions next to it. The same motif can be found on six sealings, allowing to reconstruct the full motif. EA86792, EA86793, EA86800 and EA86812 show the upper part, EA86799, EA86801 and EA86802 the lower part. description.value: Small fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The rear shows a slightly convex surface, maybe from a leather bag. Two impressions of a turned cord with a width of 0.3cm is impressed in the break. The upper side is roughly flat with the lateral sides bending downwards and showing many finger imprints. The half of an impression of an oval scarab-like seal is visible. Recognisable are two standing figures holding a staff between them. The left figure is preserved but very stylised, the figure on the right is only partly visible. The same motif is found on EA86911 and EA86915 and shows the heads preserved, probably Re-Harakhte and Amun. Both are positioned on top of a standing line. The style is very similar to the motif of EA86792, EA86793, EA86799, EA86800, EA86801, EA86802 and EA86812.

description.value: Small fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The rear shows a slightly convex surface, maybe from a leather bag. Two impressions of a turned cord with a width of 0.3cm is impressed in the break. The upper side is roughly flat with the lateral sides bending downwards and showing many finger imprints. The half of an impression of an oval scarab-like seal is visible. Recognisable are two standing figures holding a staff between them. The left figure is preserved but very stylised, the figure on the right is only partly visible. The same motif is found on EA86911 and EA86915 and shows the heads preserved, probably Re-Harakhte and Amun. Both are positioned on top of a standing line. The style is very similar to the motif of EA86792, EA86793, EA86799, EA86800, EA86801, EA86802 and EA86812.

description.value: Part of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and a partly glossy surface. description.value: Fragment of a clay seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The fragment is small and flat and shows fragments of charcoal and mica. The underside is flat and shows impressions of a basket, the side of the piece shows basketry as well, the piece was therefore placed at the rim of a basket/lid. The diameter of the basket is approximately 10 cm.  The seal impression originates from a scarab-like seal, showing a circumferential line. On the right a standing figure with white crown is shown, facing to the centre of the seal. Behind the persons head and in front of the crown each another line. The person is directed towards some sort of flowers or offering table, three stems are visible, one bigger in the middle and two smaller ones flanking each side. Above this a sun disc is shown. The area at the left is partly broken and nothing can be seen.  The number written on the object is 732 instead of 723 as the object card … (See Merlin record for full description)

description.value: Fragment of a clay seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration An almost complete sealing is preserved with two rows of basketry coil impression at the rear and one at the side, showing that this piece was positioned most likely on the lid of a basket. The fine brown Nile clay shows small inclusions of mica. The top part shows two impressions of a scarab-like seal and many finger prints around the seal impression. There are several cracks on the surface. The clay was hardened after excavation. The seal impressions are very shallow and show a circumferential band two or three figures at the shallow side. The figure on the right seems to sit on a throne, facing left, the figure on the left could be kneeling, facing right, in between them some sort of sceptre or an offering table. Above the figures a cartouche, illegible. Next to the cartouche a thickened line, maybe a winged sun disc? Same seal as used on EA86693, EA8670… (See Merlin record for full description)

description.value: Fragment of a clay seal-impression showing a concave rear with wood impression, probably originating from a peg or knob. In the break two impressions of a turned string with a width of 0.16 cm. The front shows one impression of a scarab-like seal, with the sides of the sealing bending downwards, many finger impressions around it. The seal impression is cut very sharply and shows a circumferential line that thickens at the top. The lower part of the seal is preserved, visible is a bound captive on the left side, kneeling, facing towards the left, with his hands bound together at his back. The head is broken off. Behind him on the right a seated lion, again the head is broken off, with its front paws on the shoulder of the captive. Behind the back of the lion a small upright cobra, facing to the right. Underneath a bound captive, lying on his belly, with his hands and feet bound backwards. The same motif can be found on EA86928, EA86930, EA86931, EA86932, EA86933 and EA86934 as well as o… (See Merlin record for full description)

description.value: Small fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The rear shows a convex impression like from a vessel or similar object, in the break one impression of a turned cord with a width of 0.2 cm. The front side is slightly concave, a bit more than the upper half of a seal-impression is preserved. A very thin circumferential line is visible, a horizontal line divides the seal in two rows. In the upper part a complex row of signs, in the middle a standing deity, facing towards the left, holding a wAs-sceptre in front of it. Another person to the left of the figure, a small nb-basket above it. To the right end of the upper part parts of a third figure with a staff in front of it, most broken off, partly an impression of chaff on top of the seal impression.  The lower row shows a kneeling figure with its arms raised, facing to the left and a small sing (sun disc?) to the left of its head.

description.value: Small fragment of a seal-impression, the fine brown Nile clay has some mica inclusions and was hardened after excavation. The rear shows a slightly concave area with wood impressions, probably of a knob or bolt from a box. Perpendicular to this two string impressions with a width of 0.3 cm. The front is flat with rounded edges, covered in finger impressions. In the flat area two thirds of a very round impression of a seal that seemed to have been divided into three parts by horizontal lines. The upper one is not preserved, the middle part shows a central kheper with one seated god on each side, facing inwards, the left one with a beard, the right one with a falcon(?) head and another sign above the head. In the lowest row a central Falcon facing to the left, on each side of it what looks like a stylized Hr-sign (D2). Seemed to have sealed the identical object that was closed also with EA86739 but with another seal impression on it.

description.value: Fragment of a small seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration with a partly glossy surface. The rear shows a convex surface like from a leather bag and perpendicular to this one impression of a thin turned cord with a width of 0.22 cm in the break. The front has a small flat area, the lateral sides bend downwards. On the flat part the upper half of an oval scarab-like seal-impression is preserved, showing the god Ptah in mummy-form in the middle, facing towards the left, holding a wAs-sceptre in front of him. Small hieroglyphs above this figure, nb ... (qnb.t?) . In front of him another sign, maybe two Dd-pillars with each a seated falcon on top (?). Behind the god another standing figure, maybe Sekhmet, with a sceptre in front of her, above a sun-disc. The rest is broken off. Same motif on EA86898.

The front has a small flat area, the lateral sides bend downwards. On the flat part the upper half of an oval scarab-like seal-impression is preserved, showing the god Ptah in mummy-form in the middle, facing towards the left, holding a wAs-sceptre in front of him. Small hieroglyphs above this figure, nb ... (qnb.t?) . In front of him another sign, maybe two Dd-pillars with each a seated falcon on top (?). Behind the god another standing figure, maybe Sekhmet, with a sceptre in front of her, above a sun-disc. The rest is broken off. Same motif on EA86898.

description.value: Fragment of a clay seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The fragment is showing impressions of one coil of basketry on one side and two coils of basketry on the second side, suggesting that the piece was attached between the wall and the lid of a basket. The front shows a complete impression of a scarab-like seal with disturbance in the middle part of the seal, some finger impressions around it. The seal impression shows a circumferential line that thickens at the top. Visible is a bound captive on the left side, kneeling, facing towards the left, with his hands bound together at his back. Behind him on the right a seated lion with its front paws on the shoulder of the captive. Behind the back of the lion a small upright cobra, facing to the right. Underneath a bound captive, lying on his belly, with his hands and feet bound backwards. The same motif can be found on EA86927, EA86928, EA86930, EA86931, EA86932 a… (See Merlin record for full description)

description.value: Part of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and a partly glossy surface. The rear shows a convex side with traces of an object like a leather bag or a vessel neck, in the break three deep impressions of a turned cord with a width of about 0.3 cm. EA86792, EA86793, EA86799, EA86800, EA86801, EA86802 and EA86812 all show the same motif and seem to have sealed the same object, the rear should allow a reconstruction of the sealed object.  Only a small part of the original upper side is preserved with half of a small oval scarab-like impression and lots of finger impressions next to it. The same motif can be found on six sealings, allowing to reconstruct the full motif.EA86792, EA86793, EA86800 and EA86812 show the upper part, EA86799, EA86801 and EA86802 the lower part. description.value: Small fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The rear shows a a flat surface with imprints of some organics either a plant or textile? One impression of a turned cord with a width of 0.2cm is visible in the break. The upper side is roughly flat with the lateral sides bending downwards and showing many finger imprints. Less than two thirds of an impression of an oval scarab-like seal is visible. Recognisable are two registers, the upper one shows three figures, the one on the left side seems to be seated, maybe Re-Harakhte, the middle one looks mummy-shaped with a staff in front of the body, probably Ptah. The figure on the right shows a standing female goddess also holding a staff in front of her, probably Sekhmet. The lower register shows half of a kneeling figure with the hands raised (C11). The same motif is found on EA86912 with the left part of the impression better preserved.

description.value: Fragment of a small seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation. The rear shows a bent surface with textile impression, probably from a bag. In the break an impression of a turned cord with a width of 0.25 cm.  The front is covered with finger impressions and a very small oval impression of a scarab-like seal of which the upper half is preserved. It shows a small sign on the left which could be a flag (nTr), right of it a seated Amun with double feather crown, facing to the left, behind another seated deity with red crown, facing to the left as well, behind that figure an upright uraeus. The second row is not preserved but the first sign starts with a loop like a H-sign (V28) or similar, which could be part of a horizontal sign following to the right of it. Rest is broken off.

description.value: Fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and partly a glossy surface. The rear shows a slightly convex impression of a textile or leather object, probably a bag. Two  impressions of a turned string with a width of about 0.2 cm. At the flat upper side the lower third of an impression of an oval scarab-like seal is visible, the sides are bending downwards and show many finger impressions. The seal itself is only preserved in its lower half, showing a circumferential line and originally three registers, of which two are preserved. The same motif can be found on EA86690 and EA86951. Each shows a row of seated deities. The upper one starts left with a sA-sign, then Seth facing left and behind him a deity with a sun discand the moon crescent (Khonsu?). The second register shows another seateddeity with a beard, facing to the right, in front of it remains of a kheper in the middle. description.value: Fragment of a small seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration with a partly glossy surface. The rear shows a surface that is bent almost by 90 degrees like from a leather bag and perpendicular to this three impressions of a thin turned cord with a width of 0.1-0.2 cm in the break. The front has a small flat area, the lateral sides bend downwards. On the flat part the upper half of an oval scarab-like seal-impression is preserved, showing the god Ptah in mummy-form in the middle, facing towards the left, holding a wAs-sceptre in front of him. Small hieroglyphs above this figure, nb ... (qnb.t?) . In front of him another sign, maybe two Dd-pillars with each a seated falcon on top (?). Behind the god another standing figure, maybe Sekhmet, with a sceptre in front of her, above a sun-disc. The rest is broken off. Same motif on EA86900.

On the flat part the upper half of an oval scarab-like seal-impression is preserved, showing the god Ptah in mummy-form in the middle, facing towards the left, holding a wAs-sceptre in front of him. Small hieroglyphs above this figure, nb ... (qnb.t?) . In front of him another sign, maybe two Dd-pillars with each a seated falcon on top (?). Behind the god another standing figure, maybe Sekhmet, with a sceptre in front of her, above a sun-disc. The rest is broken off. Same motif on EA86900.

description.value: Partly broken seal-impression showing basketry impression and the related string at the rear on one side, possible string and the edge of another basketry coil at the other side, meaning that this sealing probably closed the lid of a basket. The size and shape is very similar to EA86692.  The dark brown Nile clay has mica inclusions and was hardened after the excavation. Also the piece has been burnt (as has been EA86692) and shows therefore black colour at one half, and a dark brown at the other half. The front part has the impression of a scarab-like seal on the top that is partly broken off, and quite some finger prints around the seal impression. The seal shows traces of a circumferential band is cut very sharp. At the top a lying sphinx can be seen, facing to the left. Above his back an unidentified sign, in front of his head another sign. description.value: Almost complete seal-impression with two smaller rows of basketry coil impression at the rear and at the side one further rows of a larger size with small string impressions, showing that this piece was positioned most likely on the lid of a basket.  The fine brown Nile clay shows small inclusions of mica, some salt incrustations can be seen. The clay was hardened after excavation. The top part shows the impression of an oval and elongated seal that possibly originates from a ring bezel and there are some finger prints around the seal impression.  The seal impression is shallow but clearly cut and shows a circumferential band, inside one column of hieroglyphs facing to the left. The most upper sign is illegible, right of it a nfr, underneath an erected cobra (like I14 but with a shorter tail), on top of a horizontal line that could be an 'n', underneath another sign that could be kA, right of it a vertical stroke (Z1) and underneath a nb-basket. Same seal as used on EA86702.

description.value: Small fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The rear shows a slightly convex surface, maybe from a leather bag. One impression of a turned cord with a width of 0.1cm is impressed in the break. The upper side is roughly flat and upwards to the preserved side. The half of a somewhat larger impression of an oval scarab-like seal is visible, partly covered by fingerprints. The signs are quite worn and not much recognisable. The same motif is better visible on EA86901. A standing finger is preserved in the middle, wearing the double feather crown and a beard, one arm raised behind his head, the other hanging down in front of the body from where a bent sign like a uraeus(?) continues. The very small hieroglyphs left of his head are a wsr and above a seated mAa.t with a sun disc above the head, underneath the wsr a small t-sign. The rest of the seal is broken off.

description.value: Very small but complete seal-impression with two small coils of basketry on one side and one row of equally small coil of basketry on the other side, showing that this piece originates from the lid of a basket. The sealing is so small that the seal barely fit on it. The fine brown Nile clay has few inclusions of mica and shows blackening due to fire. Some salt crystals are visible as well.  The top part shows finger impressions around a scarab-like seal impression. The motif consists of four figures in different orientation. One is a lying lion arranged at the narrow end, with the rear facing towards the centre of the seal. Above it a scorpion with the tail in the same direction as the lion. Left of it what looks like another figure, only traces remain. Above the scorpion another sign that looks like the stem of a palm tree or another plant, oriented 90° to the orientation of the lion.

description.value: Small fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The rear shows a slightly convex surface with impressions of an organic material like leather, maybe from a leather bag. In the break three impressions of a turned cord with a width of 0.16cm. The upper side is flat with the lateral sides bending downwards. About a third of an impression of an oval scarab-like seal is visible. Recognisable is one of three lines in hieroglyphs, showing a very small cartouche with at least 4 signs, but a crack is running through it. The second and third lines are preserved on EA86907 and EA86919 that show the same motif. The second line is written from the right to the left: 'Imn-[R'], nfr, underneath the third row is written from the left to the right: Hr (D2) wDA.t (D10).

description.value: Fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and partly a glossy surface. It also shows blackened parts probably from fire.  The rear shows a slightly concave area with the impression of wood, probably from a bolt or a box knob, perpendicular to this two impressions of a turned cord with a width of approximately 0.20 cm.  The front side is flat which ends in a convex edge. It shows probably an impression of a seal that was impressed twice or maybe three times, with each later impression mostly overlapping the earlier impression. The shape is oval of a scarab-like seal. The motif shows a circumferential line and a standing baboon at the left, facing to the right with raised arms in front of another sign that looks like Ax.t (N27). Both are positioned on top of a simple bark. Underneath an unidentifiable sign, maybe just a decorative band.

The motif shows a circumferential line and a standing baboon at the left, facing to the right with raised arms in front of another sign that looks like Ax.t (N27). Both are positioned on top of a simple bark. Underneath an unidentifiable sign, maybe just a decorative band.
